entry.title: Revert "[PageColors] Integration of PageColors feature with NativeTheme"
entry.content:
This reverts commit da792e88b7ab6c96293af62d7ec62c7f6ecc51cf.



Reason for revert: Might be causing build failures. Examples:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Chromium%20OS%20ASan%20LSan%20Tests%20(1)/54866/overview

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/linux-chromeos-rel/71416/overview



Original change's description:

> [PageColors] Integration of PageColors feature with NativeTheme

>

> This CL makes relevant state changes to the NativeTheme web instance

> when Page colors changes. This is done in the

> ColorSchemeNativeThemeObserver::OnNativeThemeUpdated method.

>

> In the ColorSchemeNativeThemeObserver::OnNativeThemeUpdated method,

> we preserves the current behavior if Page Colors is 'Off' and forced

> colors is false OR forced colors is true and Page Colors is

> 'High Contrast'. However, if that is not the case then:

>

> 1. Page Colors is 'Off' and forced colors is true, we override the

> state of forced colors for the native theme instance for web since the

> Page colors browser setting takes precedence over OS for web content.

> Here, we also watch for changes to the preferred color scheme and make

> sure we adjust the state appropriately.

> 2. Page Colors is one of the Contrast themes i.e. 'Dusk', 'Desert',

> 'Black', 'White'. Here, we set the forced colors state to true and

> other states appropriately for web content.

>

> This CL adds the color scheme observer as a native theme observer for

> Linux in order to receive the correct state changes from

> NativeThemeAura.

>

entry.title: Revert promotion of EXT_clip_control/EXT_polygon_offset_clamp
entry.content:
Problem:



- Emscripten exposes the GL_EXTENSIONS directly from WebGL.

- Emscripten does not implement glClipControlEXT or

glPolygonOffsetClampEXT entry points.

- Chrome ships EXT_clip_control or EXT_polygon_offset_clamp.

- Existing pages on the Web that were compiled using Emscripten, from

C/C++ code that supported these extensions (like Filament), start

crashing (entry points are NULL).

from V4L2ImageProcessorBackend:

(so there's no need to Wait for Initialize() to finish anymore \o/).

- Moves methods and checks to the construction SequencedTaskRunner;

- Removes the member vars |backend_sequence_checker_| and

|backend_weak_this_/factory_|

- Introduces a convenience method TriggerPoll() for use from Create()

(also replaces a similar call elsewhere).

- Removes unnecessary |num_buffers_| member variable.



Test-wise the video.EncodeAccel and video.EncodeAccelPerf are passing

before and after. I should TAL at the performance results as well,

entry.content:
The `DirectoryModel` currently initializes an empty `DirectoryContents`

using `null`. This does not get handled in a lot of places because the

be more explicit that a `DirectoryContents` can be initialized with

functions which receive `...|undefined` and not null, so to avoid

updating all of those with `...|undefined|null` I took the smaller set

entry.title: MediaRecorder: Don't provide I420A if CanEncodeAlphaChannel() is false
entry.content:
A video encoder using media::VideoEncoder implementation in

MediaRecorder path checks I420A is provided only if

CanEncodeAlphaChannel() is true.

However, VideoTrackRecoder provides I420A to an encoder even if

CanEncodeAlphaChannel() returns false when ARGB is input to

VideoTrackRecorder. This works with its own h264 software encoder

because it converts ARGB and ABGR to I420A and then drops its alpha

channel. Although media::VideoEncoder for h264 also handles I420A

internally, it doesn't handle ARGB and ABGR. That's said, it depends

on a format whether the encoder can encode alpha channel.

It is more reasonable to convert a format and drop its alpha channel

in VideoTrackRecorder::VideoEncoder common code.



Bug: 1441395

entry.title: [CompositeClipPathAnimation] Allow worklet animations to avoid unnecessary frames
entry.content:
This change adds an additional function to PaintWorkletInput that allows for the paint worklet to avoid being invalidated if the value is not changed. This fixes an issue where composited animations with step timing functions would produce too many frames, creating a perf regression.



This is specifically done on the PaintWorkletInput level as opposed to the AnimatedPaintWorkletTracker level because composited clip path animations (and soon composited bgcolor animations) have their timing functions evaluated within the paint worklet.



This change only applies to clip path animations, however, this framework can be used for all derivations of PaintWorkletInput.

entry.title: identity.launchWebAuthFlow: center auth window for ODFS over Files app
entry.content:
Get the most recent Files app window and take its bounds, and use

these to launch the auth dialog so that it appears on top of and

centered on Files app (when launchWebAuthFlow() is called from ODFS).



This is to make auth calls from ODFS feel more associated with the

Files app window that triggered them. ODFS does not have its own UI

so we need to make this connection between the extension, Files app,

and launchWebAuthFlow(). We use a delegate for this to avoid overly

coupling the three.



This design leaves space for a lacros delegate later which can get

the necessary window bounds over crosapi. This is why the

GetOptionalWindowBounds() method is async even though it's not

strictly necessary yet.

entry.title: Apply RuntimeFeature attribute for methods in mojo cpp bindings
entry.content:
Enforces RuntimeFeature attributes on mojo methods.



```

feature kFeature {

const string name = "MyName";

const bool default_state = false;

};



interface Wolf {

[RuntimeFeature=kFeature]

EnableChaosWolf() => ();

};

```



In cpp runtime disabled methods cannot be called on remotes:



```

mojo::Remote remote;

...

remote->EnableChaosWolf(); // CHECK() failure if feature not enabled.

```



and receivers will not deserialize calls to disabled methods, causing

a normal validation failure.



Remotes are handled by adding a CHECK(feature) to the backing

generated proxy class. Receivers are handled by wrapping the

current params validation function with one that first tests

the associated feature then forwards to the normal validation

function.



Tests: mojo_unittests

Bug: 1278253
